Welles: Tisch School of the Arts at NYU                           Skip to content        Undergraduate Film & Television Admissions About the Program Course Offerings Summer Courses Showcase Internships Facilities Special Projects First Run & Festivals Calendar of Events News TSOA FTV Wiki Admin & Faculty Alumni Blog Facebook Twitter YouTube  home > Undergraduate Film & TV        Advanced Seminar: Orson Welles  H72.0700 Seminar 4.0 Credits Instructor(s): William Simon This seminar involves an intensive exploration of the artistic career of Orson Welles, placing special emphasis on his early work in theatre, radio, and film in the 1930’s and 40’s. Central topics for analysis include: 1) the relation of the works to the culture, politics, and production institutions of the periods in question, especially the New Deal and post-war America; 2) an examination of the narrative conception and structures of the work, with emphasis on the inter-relationship of narrative structure and style among the radio, theatre and film works; and 3) the theorization of Welles’ works through Bakhtin’s formulation of the dialogic. The last section of the seminar focuses on Welles post-1940’s films. The seminar draws strongly on the department’s special collection of Orson Welles materials (e.g. radio tapes, documentation of productions).
